Question 1. Calculate the population mean and standard deviation for each quantitative random variable (height, weight, age, number of zombies killed, and years of education).

#Load the csv from Github
zombies <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/fuzzyatelin/fuzzyatelin.github.io/refs/heads/master/AN588_Spring25/zombies.csv")

# Create a dataframe to store population statistics
pop_stats <- data.frame(Variable = c("height", "weight", "age", "zombies_killed", "years_of_education"), Mean = numeric(5), SD = numeric(5))

# Height
pop_stats$Mean[1] <- mean(zombies$height)
pop_stats$SD[1] <- sqrt(mean((zombies$height - mean(zombies$height))^2))

# Weight
pop_stats$Mean[2] <- mean(zombies$weight)
pop_stats$SD[2] <- sqrt(mean((zombies$weight - mean(zombies$weight))^2))

# Age
pop_stats$Mean[3] <- mean(zombies$age)
pop_stats$SD[3] <- sqrt(mean((zombies$age - mean(zombies$age))^2))

# Zombies Killed
pop_stats$Mean[4] <- mean(zombies$zombies_killed)
pop_stats$SD[4] <- sqrt(mean((zombies$zombies_killed - mean(zombies$zombies_killed))^2))

# Years of Education
pop_stats$Mean[5] <- mean(zombies$years_of_education)
pop_stats$SD[5] <- sqrt(mean((zombies$years_of_education - mean(zombies$years_of_education))^2))

# Display Results

Question 3. Use {ggplot} to make scatterplots of height and weight in relation to age. Do these variables seem to be related? In what way?

# Height vs Age
ggplot(zombies, aes(x = age, y = height)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = 'lm') + ggtitle("Height vs Age")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# Weight vs Age
ggplot(zombies, aes(x = age, y = weight)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = 'lm') + ggtitle("Weight vs Age")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Conclusion: both height and weight show positive relationships with age, meaning both increase as age increases. However, the relationship is stronger for height than for weight, suggesting age has a more direct influence on height development than on weight.

Question 4. Using histograms and Q-Q plots, check whether the quantitative variables seem to be drawn from a normal distribution. Which seem to be and which do not? For those that are not normal, can you determine from which common distribution they are drawn?

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))

# Height
hist(zombies$height, main = "Height", xlab = "Height")
qqnorm(zombies$height); qqline(zombies$height)

# Weight
hist(zombies$weight, main = "Weight", xlab = "Weight")
qqnorm(zombies$weight); qqline(zombies$weight)

# Age
hist(zombies$age, main = "Age", xlab = "Age")
qqnorm(zombies$age); qqline(zombies$age)

# Zombies Killed
hist(zombies$zombies_killed, main = "Zombies Killed", xlab = "Zombies Killed")
qqnorm(zombies$zombies_killed); qqline(zombies$zombies_killed)

# Years of Education
hist(zombies$years_of_education, main = "Years of Education", xlab = "Years of Education")
qqnorm(zombies$years_of_education); qqline(zombies$years_of_education)
par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

- Hight: the variable is a normal distribution. The histogram is symmetric and bell-shaped, and the Q-Q plots closely align with the line.

  • Weight: the variable is a normal distribution. The histogram is closely symmetric and bell-shaped, and the Q-Q plots closely align with the line.

  • Age: the variable is roughly normal. The histogram is symmetric and bell-shaped, and the Q-Q plot shows minor deviations from the line.

  • Zombies Killed: the variable is not normal. The histogram is right-skewed, and the Q-Q plot shows a deviation from the diagonal line. This should be the Poisson distribution.

  • Years of Education: this variable is not normal. The histogram is right-skewed, and the Q-Q plot shows a strong deviation from the diagonal line. This should be the Poisson distribution.

Question 5. Now use the sample() function to sample ONE subset of 30 zombie survivors (without replacement) from this population and calculate the mean and sample standard deviation for each variable. Also estimate the standard error for each variable, and construct the 95% confidence interval for each mean.

# Take a random sample of 30 zombie survivors
set.seed(123)
zombie_indices <- sample(1:nrow(zombies), 30, replace = FALSE)
sample_data <- zombies[zombie_indices, ]  # This line was missing

# Variables to analyze
variables <- c("height", "weight", "age", "zombies_killed", "years_of_education")

# Create a dataframe to store results
results <- data.frame(
  variable = variables,
  mean = numeric(length(variables)),
  sd = numeric(length(variables)),
  se = numeric(length(variables)),
  lower_ci = numeric(length(variables)),
  upper_ci = numeric(length(variables)))

# Calculate statistics for each variable
for (i in 1:length(variables)) {
  var_name <- variables[i]
  x <- sample_data[[var_name]]
  
  results$mean[i] <- mean(x)
  results$sd[i] <- sd(x)
  results$se[i] <- sd(x)/sqrt(length(x))
  t_critical <- qt(0.975, df = length(x) - 1)
  results$lower_ci[i] <- results$mean[i] - t_critical * results$se[i]
  results$upper_ci[i] <- results$mean[i] + t_critical * results$se[i]
}

# Print the results
print(results)

Question 6. Now draw 99 more random samples of 30 zombie apocalypse survivors, and calculate the mean for each variable for each of these samples. Together with the first sample you drew, you now have a set of 100 means for each variable (each based on 30 observations), which constitutes a sampling distribution for each variable. What are the means and standard deviations of this distribution of means for each variable? How do the standard deviations of means compare to the standard errors estimated in [5]? What do these sampling distributions look like (a graph might help here)? Are they normally distributed? What about for those variables that you concluded were not originally drawn from a normal distribution?

# Set seed
set.seed(123)

# Create matrix to store 100 sample means
sample_means <- matrix(0, nrow = 100, ncol = length(variables))
colnames(sample_means) <- variables

# Draw 100 samples and calculate means
for(i in 1:100) {zombie_sample <- zombies[sample(1:nrow(zombies), 30), ]
  for(j in 1:length(variables)) {sample_means[i, j] <- mean(zombie_sample[[variables[j]]])}}

# Convert to dataframe for easier analysis
sample_means <- as.data.frame(sample_means)

# Calculate sampling distribution statistics
results <- data.frame(Varibles = variables, Mean = sapply(sample_means, mean),SD = sapply(sample_means, sd),SE = sapply(variables, function(v) sd(zombies[[v]])/sqrt(30)))

print(results)
##                              Varibles       Mean        SD        SE
## height                         height  67.694844 0.6765653 0.7869177
## weight                         weight 143.947208 2.9991708 3.3595585
## age                               age  20.072396 0.4878208 0.5413444
## zombies_killed         zombies_killed   2.958333 0.3425125 0.3192174
## years_of_education years_of_education   3.019000 0.3160238 0.3060934
# Create QQ plots
par(mfrow = c(2, 3))
for(var in variables) {qqnorm(sample_means[[var]], main = paste("QQ Plot:", var))
  qqline(sample_means[[var]], col = "red")}

- Comparing Standard Deviations to Standard Errors The standard deviations of the sampling distributions should closely match the standard errors calculated in question 5. This confirms the statistical theory that the standard deviation of sample means equals σ/√n.

  • Normality of Sampling Distributions For variables that were originally normally distributed (height, weight, age), their sampling distributions is also be normal. For zombies_killed and years of education, even these non-normal variables will have approximately normal sampling distributions, the Q-Q plots show points much closer to the diagonal line and all sampling distributions will appear roughly normal. This demonstrates why we can apply many statistical tests to means even when the original data isn’t normal, as long as the sample size is large enough (n≥30).
